<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="244" pageId="4" pageNumber="243" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1917,2015]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,151,466]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="244" pageId="4" pageNumber="243">
This distinctive species was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[667,725,1917,1943]" name="India" pageId="4" pageNumber="243">India</collectingCountry>
in a monobasic genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karny" authorityYear="1926" box="[999,1214,1917,1943]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Ramaswamiahiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[999,1214,1917,1943]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="243">Ramaswamiahiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but was placed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Palmer, J. M." box="[151,311,1953,1979]" pageId="4" pageNumber="243" pagination="1 - 76" refId="ref4189" refString="Palmer, J. M. (1992) Thrips (Thysanoptera) from Pakistan to the Pacific: a review. Bulletin British Museum Natural History, Entomology, 61, 1 - 76." type="journal article" year="1992">Palmer (1992)</bibRefCitation>
in her “Group IV” of genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[623,696,1953,1979]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[623,696,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="243">Thrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The species in that group bear an unusually large number of setae, on the pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[348,429,1989,2015]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–15" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1666,1690]" captionTargetBox="[311,1273,417,1643]" captionTargetId="figure-127@4.[311,1275,417,1643]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 13–15. Thrips brevistylus (13) Meso- and metanotum; Thrips subnudula (14) Pronotum, meso- and metanotum, (15) abdominal stenites III–VI." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4501870" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4501870/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="243">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
), sternites and pleurotergites. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Karny" baseAuthorityYear="1926" box="[760,903,1989,2015]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="243" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subnudula">
<emphasis box="[760,903,1989,2015]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="243">T. subnudula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unusual in having the sternal posteromarginal setae duplicated, such that there are usually 12 setae across the margins of sternites III–VI. There are 14–16 sternal discal setae, and 4–8 pleurotergal discal setae (
<figureCitation box="[666,748,186,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–15" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1666,1690]" captionTargetBox="[311,1273,417,1643]" captionTargetId="figure-127@4.[311,1275,417,1643]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 13–15. Thrips brevistylus (13) Meso- and metanotum; Thrips subnudula (14) Pronotum, meso- and metanotum, (15) abdominal stenites III–VI." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4501870" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4501870/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). It is a small pale species, with 7-segmented antennae, ocellar setae pair III arising behind the first ocellus, and with the posteromarginal comb on tergite VIII broadly interrupted medially. In 
<collectingCountry box="[293,351,259,285]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">India</collectingCountry>
this species is associated with the weedy plant 
<taxonomicName box="[886,1185,259,285]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Parthenium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hysterophorus">
<emphasis box="[886,1185,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Parthenium hysterophorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it has been found widely across Asia between 
<collectingCountry box="[477,572,295,321]" name="Pakistan" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
and northern 
<collectingCountry box="[733,839,295,321]" name="Australia" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Australia</collectingCountry>
. It is also recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[1131,1215,295,321]" name="Nigeria" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Nigeria</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Palmer, J. M." box="[1231,1378,295,321]" pageId="5" pageNumber="244" pagination="1 - 76" refId="ref4189" refString="Palmer, J. M. (1992) Thrips (Thysanoptera) from Pakistan to the Pacific: a review. Bulletin British Museum Natural History, Entomology, 61, 1 - 76." type="journal article" year="1992">Palmer 1992</bibRefCitation>
) and apparently 
<collectingCountry box="[278,365,331,357]" name="Uganda" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Uganda</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[424,569,331,357]" name="South Africa" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(see zur Strassen list in ThripsWiki 2020), but this is the first record of the species from 
<collectingCountry box="[300,406,367,393]" name="Malaysia" pageId="5" pageNumber="244">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
